HEADWORD: Lyceum
<hw>Ly*ce"um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> E.
<plw>Lyceums</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, L. <plw>Lycea</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu>
<ety>[L. <ets>lyceum</ets>, Gr. <?/, so named after the neighboring
temple of <?/ <?/ Apollo the wolf slayer, prob. fr. <?/ belonging to a
wolf, fr <?/ wolf. See <er>Wolf</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A place of
exercise with covered walks, in the suburbs of Athens, where Aristotle
taught philosophy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A house or apartment appropriated to instruction by
lectures or disquisitions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A higher school, in Europe, which prepares youths
for the university.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An association for debate and literary
improvement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lyche</ent>⟦br⟧
